'''Hypersensitivity''' (also called '''hypersensitivity reaction''') refers to undesirable reactions produced by the normal immune system, including [[allergies]] and [[autoimmunity]]. These reactions may be damaging, uncomfortable, or occasionally fatal.  Hypersensitivity reactions require a pre-sensitized (immune) state of the host. The four-group classification was expounded by [[Philip George Houthem Gell|P. H. G. Gell]] and [[Robin Coombs]] in 1963.<ref>Gell PGH, Coombs RRA, eds. Clinical Aspects of Immunology. 1st ed. Oxford, England: Blackwell; 1963.</ref>

